{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/learning-to-use-progress-bars-in-python-2dc436de81e5", "time": 1683002387.923255, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/learning-to-use-progress-bars-in-python-2dc436de81e5/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Learning to Use Progress Bars in Python | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How to Use Progress Bars in Python", "description": "Progress Bars are a visual representation of how long is left for a process to complete. Learn how to use them in command line (Progress, tqdm, Alive Progress) and PySimpleGUI."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://pypi.org/project/progress/1.5/", "anchor_text": "documentation", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://github.com/tqdm/tqdm", "anchor_text": "documentation", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://github.com/rsalmei/alive-progress", "anchor_text": "different features", "paragraph_index": 12}, {"url": "https://medium.com/u/bc85c7e63ea3?source=post_page-----2dc436de81e5--------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Mike", "paragraph_index": 15}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/learn-how-to-quickly-create-uis-in-python-a97ae1394d5", "anchor_text": "quickly spin up Python UIs", "paragraph_index": 16}, {"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/building-a-python-ui-for-comparing-data-13c10693d9e4", "anchor_text": "comparison tool with a UI", "paragraph_index": 16}], "all_paragraphs": ["Progress Bars are a visual representation of how long is left for a process to complete. They save you having to worry whether the process has hang or try to predict how your code has been getting on. You can visually see in real time how well the script is progressing!", "If you have never thought of or worked with progress bars before, it\u2019s easy to assume that they would add unnecessary complexity to your code and would be hard to maintain. It couldn\u2019t be further from the truth. In just a couple lines of code, we will see how to add progress bars to both our command line scripts, but also our PySimpleGUI UIs.", "The first python library to review is Progress.", "All you need to do is define the number of iterations you expect to do, the type of bar and let the bar know at every iteration.", "If you don\u2019t like the format of the progress bar, there are many for you to choose from:", "Don\u2019t forget to check out their documentation.", "Next up in our review, is the tqdm library.", "A Fast, Extensible Progress Bar for Python and CLI", "Much like the previous library, we\u2019ve seen, with a couple of lines we can introduce a progres bar. Only a slight difference in terms of the set up:", "Same as before, the bar does come with a few options. Do make sure to check the documentation.", "This library, as the name suggests, attempts to bring the progress bar alive. It has a few more animations than the previous progress bars we\u2019ve seen. In terms of code, it\u2019s pretty similar however:", "With the bar looking as expected:", "Once again, don\u2019t forget to explore the library\u2019s different features.", "In the same spirit that we\u2019ve seen so far, we can add a single line of code to get a graphical progress bar to our command line script.", "To achieve the above, all we need is:", "Thanks Mike for pointing this out!", "If you have been following my latest blogs, we explored how to quickly spin up Python UIs and then we built a comparison tool with a UI. To continue our learning journey, today we will explore how to integrate a progress bar.", "This is it guys! With only a few lines of code you can implement progress bars in your python scripts! It\u2019s nothing too complicated and you no longer have to guess as to how your script is getting on!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "A technologist with domain expertise in Investment Banking"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F2dc436de81e5&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppB